============================================================
Terraform Provisioners:
============================================================

Definition:
Provisioners are used to execute scripts or commands on a resource
after it is created (or before it is destroyed).
They act as a "last-mile" configuration step.

------------------------------------------------------------
Types of Provisioners:
------------------------------------------------------------
1. file        -> Copy files from local machine to resource
2. remote-exec -> Run commands on remote resource (SSH/WinRM)
3. local-exec  -> Run commands on local machine

------------------------------------------------------------
Real-Time Use Case:
------------------------------------------------------------
Scenario:
Launch an AWS EC2 instance and automatically install Nginx / httpd 
so that the server is ready immediately after creation.

------------------------------------------------------------
Terraform Configuration Example:
------------------------------------------------------------

resource "aws_instance" "prod_server" {
  
  ami = "ami-0f559c3642608c138"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
  key_name = "madhukiran"

    network_interface {
        device_index = 0
        network_interface_id = aws_network_interface.prod_eni.id
    }


  tags = {
    Name = "Prod-fb-Server"
  }

provisioner "local-exec" {
  command = "echo 'this is facebook server IP: ${aws_eip.prod_eip.public_ip}' > fb-server-ip.txt"
}

connection {
  type = "ssh"
  user = "ec2-user"
  private_key = file("C:/Users/Madhukiran/Desktop/keys/madhukiran.pem")
  host = aws_eip.prod_eip.public_ip
}

provisioner "file" {
  source = "index.html"
  destination = "/tmp/indx.html"
}

provisioner "remote-exec" {
  inline = [
    "sudo yum install httpd -y",
    "sudo cp /tmp/indx.html /var/www/html/index.html",
    "sudo systemctl start httpd", 
    "sudo systemctl enable httpd",
  ]

}

}

------------------------------------------------------------
Execution Flow:
------------------------------------------------------------
1. Terraform creates EC2 instance
2. Establishes SSH connection using key pair
3. Executes commands on the instance
4. Nginx/Httpd  is installed and running

------------------------------------------------------------
Important Notes:
------------------------------------------------------------
- Provisioners are NOT recommended for regular use
- They are not fully idempotent (may cause issues if re-run)
- Should be used only when no better alternative exists

------------------------------------------------------------
Preferred Alternatives:
------------------------------------------------------------
- user_data / cloud-init scripts
- Configuration management tools (Ansible, Chef, Puppet)

------------------------------------------------------------
Summary:
------------------------------------------------------------
Provisioners = Post-creation automation
Useful for quick setup tasks
Use sparingly in production environments
============================================================


============================================================
Terraform Provisioners vs AWS User Data 
============================================================

Definition:

Terraform Provisioners:
Provisioners execute scripts or commands AFTER a resource is created.
They connect to the resource (SSH/WinRM) and run commands.

AWS User Data:
User data is a script that runs DURING the instance boot process.
It is passed at launch time and executed automatically by the OS.

------------------------------------------------------------
Key Differences:
------------------------------------------------------------

1. Execution Time:
Provisioners  -> After resource creation
User Data     -> During instance startup (boot time)

2. Dependency:
Provisioners  -> Requires network access (SSH/WinRM)
User Data     -> No external connection required

3. Reliability:
Provisioners  -> Less reliable (can fail if connection fails)
User Data     -> More reliable (runs internally on instance)

4. Idempotency:
Provisioners  -> Not fully idempotent
User Data     -> Can be made idempotent with scripting

5. Terraform Role:
Provisioners  -> Last resort feature in Terraform
User Data     -> Preferred method for initialization

------------------------------------------------------------
Real-Time Example Comparison:
------------------------------------------------------------

Using Provisioner:

resource "aws_instance" "example1" {
  ami           = "ami-123456"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  connection {
    type        = "ssh"
    user        = "ec2-user"
    private_key = file("key.pem")
    host        = self.public_ip
  }

  provisioner "remote-exec" {
    inline = [
      "sudo yum install nginx -y",
      "sudo systemctl start nginx"
    ]
  }
}

------------------------------------------------------------

Using User Data:

resource "aws_instance" "example2" {
  ami           = "ami-123456"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"

  user_data = <<-EOF
              #!/bin/bash
              yum install nginx -y
              systemctl start nginx
              systemctl enable nginx
              EOF
}

------------------------------------------------------------
Execution Flow Difference:
------------------------------------------------------------

Provisioner Flow:
1. Terraform creates EC2
2. Waits for instance to be ready
3. Connects via SSH
4. Executes commands

User Data Flow:
1. Terraform creates EC2
2. Instance boots
3. Script runs automatically inside instance
4. No external connection needed

------------------------------------------------------------
Best Practice:
------------------------------------------------------------

Use User Data:
- For installing packages
- For bootstrapping instances
- For production environments

Use Provisioners:
- Only when user_data is not sufficient
- For edge cases or quick fixes

------------------------------------------------------------
Summary:
------------------------------------------------------------

Provisioners = External, post-creation configuration
User Data    = Internal, boot-time initialization

User Data is preferred over Provisioners in most real-world scenarios
