TERRAFORM VARIABLE DATA TYPE CONSTRAINTS


---

1. WHAT ARE DATA TYPE CONSTRAINTS?

Data type constraints define what kind of value a variable can accept.


         String → only text
         Number → only numbers
         List → multiple values
         Object → structured data
		 map --> key value pair 
        
Purpose:

         Avoid mistakes
         Make code predictable
         Improve readability

---

2. STRING (text)

Definition:
A string is just text inside quotes.


variable "region" {
   type = string
}

Input:
region = "us-east-1"

Real-time use:

* AWS region
* Resource names
* Environment (dev, prod)

============================================================

3. NUMBER

Definition:
Used for numeric values.

Example:
variable "instance_count" {
type = number
}

Input:
instance_count = 3

Real-time use:

* Number of servers
* Disk size (GB)
* Autoscaling limits

---

4. BOOL (true/false)

Definition:
Boolean values: true or false

Example:
variable "enable_public_ip" {
type = bool
}

Input:
enable_public_ip = true

Real-time use:

* Enable or disable public IP
* Turn features ON or OFF

---

5. LIST (ordered values)

Definition:
A list holds multiple values in order.

Example:

variable "subnet_cidrs" {
      type = list(string)
               }

Input:
subnet_cidrs = [
         "10.0.1.0/24",
         "10.0.2.0/24"
               ]

Real-time use:

* Subnets
* Availability zones
* Security group IDs

---

6. MAP (key-value pairs)

Definition:
Stores data as key = value

Example:

variable "tags" {
type = map(string)
}

Input:

tags = {
Name = "web-server"
Env  = "dev"
owner = "madhu"
}

Real-time use:

* Resource tagging in AWS
* Labels and metadata

---

7. OBJECT (structured data)

Definition:
An object groups multiple fields together.

Example:

variable "server_config" {
          type = object({
                     name  = string
                     size  = string
                     count = number
                       })
          }

Input:
server_config = {
name  = "web"
size  = "t2.micro"
count = 2
}

Real-time use:

* Server configuration
* Database settings
* Application configs

---

8. LIST OF OBJECTS (IMPORTANT)

Definition:
A list containing multiple objects.

Example:

variable "public_subnets" {
  description = "List of public subnets with CIDR and Availability Zone"
  type = list(object({
    cidr = string
    az   = string
  }))


Input:
public_subnets = [
{ cidr = "10.0.1.0/24", az = "us-east-1a" },
{ cidr = "10.0.2.0/24", az = "us-east-1b" }
]

Real-time use:

* Multiple subnets in multiple availability zones 
* Multiple servers
* Multiple environments

---

9. WHY TYPE CONSTRAINTS ARE IMPORTANT

10. Prevent errors
    Example:
    instance_count = "three"  (wrong type)

11. Validate structure
    Example:
    public_subnets = "10.0.1.0/24" (should be list)

12. Improve readability

13. Help teamwork (others understand input format easily)

---

10. SIMPLE ANALOGY

## Type           → Real-life example

string         → Name
number         → Age
bool           → Yes or No
list           → Shopping list
map            → Dictionary (word → meaning)
object         → Form with fields
list(object)   → Multiple forms

---

11. FINAL SUMMARY

* Terraform variables need correct data types
* Types ensure correct input format
* Common types: string, number, bool, list, map, object
* Most used in real projects: list(object)

